column1: Between 1 January 2021 and 31 December 2022, will a firm or paid backup driver operating a self-driving vehicle face criminal charges in relation to an accident involving a self-driving vehicle in the U.S.?
column5: ['Yes, a firm', 'Yes, a paid backup driver', 'Yes, both', 'No']
column6: ['Business', 'Technology']
Criminal prosecution would lose an indescribable quantity of investment money that's been dumped into autonomous driving.

Assisted and autonomous vehicles will have a larger share of cars on the road. Depending on the nature of the accident either a firm or a backup driver could face charges that may later be dismissed. There are business interests that may work to isolate the impact by individualizing the accident to a unique situation, manufacturer, malfunction, driver, or external variable. This isolation will emphasize fault away from the trend towards autonomous driving.

I can't recall my past reasoning but after thinking for 10 minutes by the clock I see the following considerations: * One case in five+ years implies something like 60%..80% for the "No". * I think that companies would prefer an out-of-court settlement for ~PR reasons, which makes "Yes, a firm" and "Yes, both" not particularly likely. * One might want to go higher on "No" if one expects to get notified in advance e.g. the time between the crash which resolved the short-term question and the charges was ~2.5 years and caused Uber to pause their self-driving tests.

Relevant factors are miles driven autonomously, chance of accident at large and variance of chances with autonomous technology, and chance of failure of autonomous technology resulting in actual legal liability. In other words 3 causes: 1) actual tech failure resulting in legal liability, which I put at 0% given relatively few miles driven and current trends and results in tech, 2) involvement in a fatal accident but unclear liability resulting charges, also at 0% given miles driven, or 3) 5% to account for involvement in a serious accident and charges brought for political or other reasons, which is unlikely but certainly possible depending on unclear liability, sympathetic ‘victim’ and a jurisdiction opposed to autonomous vehicles for whatever reason.

This is based more on knowledge of tort evolution than current research. We already know that the likelihood of a fatal crash involving a driver-assisted AV is almost certain, just given the proliferation of opportunities. One fatality is insignificant when compared to those caused by human drivers. But, nonetheless --it will take only one to generate lawsuits. And since the firm has the deep pockets, they are the likely target, with subordinate suits against the driver.

Firms are careful to say that drivers need to be attentive and prepared to take over a self driving vehicle in order to limit their liability. The most publicized case was when an Uber car killed a pedestrian. The result was the backup driver but not the firm being charged. (https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-54175359) There is also a push within the U.S. to hold technology firms in general more accountable and this could expand into the self-driving vehicle sector. The timeframe of this question is significant and with the proliferation of self-driving vehicles it is likely that more criminal charges will be filed.

A case filed against is not the same as a case decided against. Assuming that more autonomous vehicles hit the road, such a case is high likely within a two year time frame. It would be a surprise if the case was filed against either a firm or a driver rather than a firm and a driver.

Depending on how the trial goes with the hired back-up driver in Arizona, there is a chance Uber could face charges, although this is unlikely since it appears Uber has been cleared of wrongdoing.

The danger with autonomous vehicles is when people don't understand the limits and they don't have good knowledge of under what conditions the human should take over. You can read stories about people sleeping in their Tesla while it goes down the freeway at 90 miles per hour on autopilot. however, I tend to think that paid backup drivers and professional firms will be more like airline pilots with very good understanding of when to use the autopilot and when the human should take over.
*Criminal charges? Highly unlikely. This tech is still a long distance away from public/common usage.

While the probability of self driving commercial vehicles operating in 2021-22 is unlikely, there are still many autonomous commercial vehicles in operation, which makes probably of a serious accident very likely. Once a serious accident happens, the odds that some charges are filed are also very high. This is an unsettled area of law, and some authority will want to try to make a test case out of the incident. I think the driver is more likely to be charged than the firm, but the most likely outcome is that either both are charged in the same incident or at least one of each is charged in separate incidents.

I think the probability of self driving commercial vehicles operating in 2021-22 is high but not 100%. Given that autonomous commercial vehicles are in operation, the probably of a serious accident is near 1 (unless deployment is so small there aren't many miles driven). Conditional of the accident happening, I think the odds that some charges are filed are also very high. This is an unsettled area of law, and some authority will want to try to make a test case out of the incident. I think the driver is more likely to be charged than the firm, but the most likely outcome is that either both are charged in the same incident or at least one of each is charged in separate incidents.

Self-driving vehicles will likely still be extremely uncommon, meaning that there will be few accidents overall. I find it likely that there will be civil cases against both parties, but I'm not sure prosecutors will be eager to pursue criminal cases with so little precedent. Probability of "both" should be lower than probability of "driver" and "firm" since its a more exclusive category.
Firms have legal disclosures absolving them from any responsibility for accidents. Hard to prove individual driver’s negligence.

The probability should be the same as with the short-term, but I think adjusting the numbers is acceptable since many factors will complicate the final outcome (more companies testing, more AVs on the road, etc.)

Right now, it appears to be highly unlikely that "criminal charges" will be brought against a company or a person, for an "accident" (I have issue with this language as it is very vague; isn't it for the court to determine whether something was an 'accident,' in this instance?) involving an autonomous vehicle.
This is America. People will sue for anything. Whether justified or not both will be tested.

With insurance, there is a portion of blame assessed for each party being at the scene of an accident. The fact there is talk of having a backup driver there shows that firms would be trying to mitigate risk to start with. A person is responsible for his or her own actions and inactions under the law. There is a bigger risk for firms rather than individuals of being sued by the victim for the crime. The individual would be more responsible for criminal misconduct charges.
This is for two full years. Lawyers will jump at the opportunity to set legal president for any case that involves a self driving car.

The time window of 2 years is long enough for both to happen. 10% chance seems pretty high for this to happen in this timeframe considering the prior years of operation. The difference is that there will be a lot more miles on the road in 2021 with vastly more sophisticated control than in the past. Thus there are far more opportunities.
